Afdød","1352–Male":"1352–Afdød","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1380–1460":"1380–1460","–Male":"Afdød","1337":"1337","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1440":"1440","1460":"1460","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","about 1352":"omkring 1352","1380":"1380","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Chaddesley Corbett, Worcestershire, England":"Chaddesley Corbett, Worcestershire, England"},"nl":{"1330–":"1330–Overleden","1330–Female":"1330–Overleden","1320–Male":"1320–Overleden","1352–Male":"1352–Overleden","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1380–1460":"1380–1460","–Male":"Overleden","1337":"1337","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1440":"1440","1460":"1460","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","about 1352":"circa 1352","1380":"1380","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Chaddesley Corbett, Worcestershire, England":"Chaddesley Corbett, Worcestershire, England"},"en":{"1330–":"1330–Deceased","1330–Female":"1330–Deceased","1320–Male":"1320–Deceased","1352–Male":"1352–Deceased","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1380–1460":"1380–1460","–Male":"Deceased","1337":"1337","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1440":"1440","1460":"1460","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","about 1352":"about 1352","1380":"1380","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Chaddesley Corbett, Worcestershire, England":"Chaddesley Corbett, Worcestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cortwright","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Midlands and northern England): occupational name from Middle English <i>cart(e)</i> ‘cart’ + <i>wright(e)</i> ‘craftsman’ (Old English <i>cræt</i> or Old Norse <i>kartr</i> + Old English <i>wyrhta</i>), for a cartwright, a maker of carts.","Variant of   Courtright  , a surname of Dutch origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Gathright","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Cartwright  ."]},{"name":"Catrett","meanings":["Altered form of English   Cartwright  ."]},{"name":"Cartright","meanings":["English (Staffordshire): variant of   Cartwright  .","Probably also a variant of   Courtright  , a surname of Dutch origin."]},{"name":"Cartrette","meanings":["English: altered form of   Cartwright  ."]},{"name":"Courtright","meanings":["Americanized form of Dutch <b>Kortrijk</b>: habitational name from the city of Kortrijk in Flanders, in French known as Courtrai. Compare   Cartwright  ,   Cortright  ,   Courtwright  ,   Curtright  ,   Cutright  , and   Kortright  .","Perhaps also an altered form of English   Cartwright  .","History: The progenitors of the (majority of the) Courtrights (and Cortrights, Kortrights, etc.) were the brothers Jan and Michiel Bastiansen van Kortryk from Leerdam in the Netherlands, who arrived with their families to New Amsterdam in New Netherland (now New York City, NY) in 1663. The descendants of one or another brother also bear the surnames <i>Kortright</i>, <i>Kortwright</i>, <i>Cortright</i>, <i>Co(u)rtwright</i>, <i>Cartwright</i>, and <i>Cu(r)tright</i>."]}]},{"name":"Diana","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Name borne in Roman mythology by the goddess of the moon and of hunting, equivalent to the Greek Artemis. In mythology she is characterized as both beautiful and chaste. Her name is of ancient and uncertain derivation. It probably contains a first element that is also found in the name of the Greek god <i>Dionysos</i> (  see  Dennis  ) and the Latin name of the supreme god <i>Jupiter</i>. It was adopted in Britain during the Tudor period as a learned name, a borrowing from Latin influenced by the French form   Diane .  Although it was much used by Elizabethan poets celebrating the virgin goddess and alluding to the Virgin Queen, it was not particularly popular as a given name until the end of the 19th century. In earlier centuries some clergymen were reluctant to baptize girls with this pagan name, mindful of the riots against St Paul stirred up by worshippers of Diana of the Ephesians (Acts 19:24–41). In the late 20th century, its popularity received a boost because of its association with the late  Diana , Princess of Wales (  1961–97 ), who was renowned for her beauty, glamour, and compassion."],"variants":[{"name":"Dianna","meanings":["Name borne in Roman mythology by the goddess of the moon and of hunting, equivalent to the Greek Artemis. In mythology she is characterized as both beautiful and chaste. Her name is of ancient and uncertain derivation. It probably contains a first element that is also found in the name of the Greek god <i>Dionysos</i> (  see  Dennis  ) and the Latin name of the supreme god <i>Jupiter</i>. It was adopted in Britain during the Tudor period as a learned name, a borrowing from Latin influenced by the French form   Diane .  Although it was much used by Elizabethan poets celebrating the virgin goddess and alluding to the Virgin Queen, it was not particularly popular as a given name until the end of the 19th century. In earlier centuries some clergymen were reluctant to baptize girls with this pagan name, mindful of the riots against St Paul stirred up by worshippers of Diana of the Ephesians (Acts 19:24–41). In the late 20th century, its popularity received a boost because of its association with the late  Diana , Princess of Wales (  1961–97 ), who was renowned for her beauty, glamour, and compassion."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":7,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":52,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Diana Cortwright was born in 1330, in Chaddesley Corbett, Worcestershire, England as the daughter of Mr Cortwright. She married William Wakeman in 1352, in Worcestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"1330–":"1330–Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1352–Male":"1352–Surnud","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1380–1460":"1380–1460","–Male":"Surnud","1337":"1337","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1440":"1440","1460":"1460","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","about 1352":"umbes 1352","1380":"1380","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chaddesley Corbett, Worcestershire, England":"Chaddesley Corbett, Worcestershire, England"},"fi":{"1330–":"1330–Kuollut","1330–Female":"1330–Kuollut","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","1352–Male":"1352–Kuollut","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1380–1460":"1380–1460","–Male":"Kuollut","1337":"1337","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1440":"1440","1460":"1460","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","about 1352":"noin 1352","1380":"1380","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Chaddesley Corbett, Worcestershire, England":"Chaddesley Corbett, Worcestershire, England"},"fr":{"1330–":"1330–Décédée","1330–Female":"1330–Décédée","1320–Male":"1320–Décédé","1352–Male":"1352–Décédé","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1380–1460":"1380–1460","–Male":"Décédé","1337":"1337","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1440":"1440","1460":"1460","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","about 1352":"environ 1352","1380":"1380","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Chaddesley Corbett, Worcestershire, England":"Chad